column1: A unique identifier assigned to a material sample by the reseacher. Shipped sample information and identifier
column3: Unique ID assigned to parent sample (IGSN or ARK)
column5: Study ID in the GOLD database
column6: Unique ID assigned to the Biosample in the GOLD database
column7: Sequencing project ID of the sample available in GOLD database
column9: Data target from EMSL
column10: The site (ecological, not geological) from where the sample was collected
column11: Broad ecosystem of the sample (Engineered / Host-associated / Environmental)
column12: The categoy of the sample ecosystem (ex: air/aquatic/terrestrial)
column13: Type of the sample ecosystem (ex: soil/cave)
column14: Subtype of the sample ecosystem (ex: loam/sand)
column15: Specific ecosystem of the sample (Agricultural soil / forest soil)
column17: The geographical origin of the sample as defined by the country or sea name followed by specific region name.
column18: The geographical origin of the sample as defined by latitude and longitude. The values should be reported in decimal degrees and in WGS84 system
column19: The geographical origin of the sample as defined by latitude and longitude. The values should be reported in decimal degrees and in WGS84 system
column20: Depth is defined as the vertical distance below local surface, e.g. For sediment or soil samples depth is measured from sediment or soil surface, respectively. Depth can be reported as an interval for subsurface samples
column22: Elevation of the sampling site is its height above a fixed reference point, most commonly the mean sea level. Elevation is mainly used when referring to points on the earth's surface, while altitude is used for points above the surface, such as an aircraft in flight or a spacecraft in orbit
column23: Name of the project within which the sequencing was organized
column24: Nucleic Acid Sequence Report is the root element of all MIGS/MIMS compliant reports as standardized by Genomic Standards Consortium. This field is either eukaryote,bacteria,virus,plasmid,organelle, metagenome,mimarks-survey, mimarks-specimen, metatranscriptome, single amplified genome, metagenome-assembled genome, or uncultivated viral genome
column25: Ph measurement of the sample, or liquid portion of sample, or aqueous phase of the fluid
column27: Volume (ml) of processed sample, or surface area swabbed from sample for DNA extraction
column29: Vegetation classification from one or more standard classification systems, or agricultural crop
column30: Reference or method used in vegetation classification
column32: Reference or method used in determining previous land use and dates
column33: Whether or not crop is rotated, and if yes, rotation schedule
column34: Addition of fertilizers, pesticides, etc. - amount and time of applications
column36: Historical and/or physical evidence of fire
column37: Historical and/or physical evidence of flooding
column38: Unusual physical events that may have affected microbial populations
column39: Specific layer in the land area which measures parallel to the soil surface and possesses physical characteristics which differ from the layers above and beneath
column40: Reference or method used in determining the horizon
column41: Collection design of pooled samples and/or sieve size and amount of sample sieved
column43: Reference or method used in determining the water content of soil
column44: Weight (g) of processed sample, or surface area swabbed from sample for DNA extraction
column45: Indicate whether multiple DNA extractions were mixed. If the answer yes, the number of extracts that were pooled should be given
column46: Explain how and for how long the soil sample was stored before DNA extraction
column50: The average of all annual precipitation values known, or an estimated equivalent value derived by such methods as regional indexes or Isohyetal maps.
column51: The average of all seasonal precipitation values known, or an estimated equivalent value derived by such methods as regional indexes or Isohyetal maps.
column52: Link to digitized soil maps or other soil classification information
column53: Soil classification from the FAO World Reference Database for Soil Resources. The list can be found at http://www.fao.org/nr/land/sols/soil/wrb-soil-maps/reference-groups
column54: Soil classification based on local soil classification system
column55: Reference or method used in determining the local soil classification
column56: Soil series name or other lower-level classification
column57: Reference or method used in determining soil series name or other lower-level classification
column58: Commonly called 'slope'. The angle between ground surface and a horizontal line (in percent). This is the direction that overland water would flow. This measure is usually taken with a hand level meter or clinometer
column59: The direction a slope faces. While looking down a slope use a compass to record the direction you are facing (direction or degrees); e.g., nw or 315 degrees. This measure provides an indication of sun and wind exposure that will influence soil temperature and evapotranspiration.
column60: Cross-sectional position in the hillslope where sample was collected.sample area position in relation to surrounding areas
column61: Drainage classification from a standard system such as the USDA system
column62: The relative proportion of different grain sizes of mineral particles in a soil, as described using a standard system; express as % sand (50 um to 2 mm), silt (2 um to 50 um), and clay (<2 um) with textural name (e.g., silty clay loam) optional.
column63: Reference or method used in determining soil texture
column64: Reference or method used in determining ph
column65: Definition for soil: total organic carbon content of the soil, definition otherwise: total organic carbon content
column66: Reference or method used in determining total organic carbon
column67: Total nitrogen content of the sample
column68: Reference or method used in determining the total nitrogen
column69: The part of the organic matter in the soil that constitutes living microorganisms smaller than 5-10 micrometer. If you keep this, you would need to have correction factors used for conversion to the final units
column70: Reference or method used in determining microbial biomass
column71: Link to additional analysis results performed on the sample
column72: Reference or method used in determining salinity
column73: Heavy metals present and the frequency of usage; can include multiple heavy metals and concentrations
column74: Reference or method used in determining heavy metals
column76: Reference or method used in determining Al saturation
column77: Publication reference in the form of pubmed ID (pmid), digital object identifier (doi) or url for isolation and growth condition specifications of the organism/material
column78: Any other measurement performed or parameter collected, that is not listed here
column80: NCBI Biosample access of the given sample
column82: The name of the sequencing project
column84: Name of the environmental package used for reporting of measurements and observations obtained
column85: Name of the stdy in the GOLD database
column88: Any other information about the sample
column89: Enter verified if the geographic coordinates were actually captured at sampling event. If determined after sampling even by Google maps etc. enter inferred.
column90: Pressure to which the sample is subject to, in atmospheres
column91: Concentration of nitrate in the sample

column94: If depth is in range, the second value comes here

column104: Sample taxonomy ID given in NCBI

column106: The location from where the sample was collected
